{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.01,0.06,0.05,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45729"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30651"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"303"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45729"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 8-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of cough and audible wheeze. He has also been feeding poorly during this time. He had been well up until this. He has a 4-year-old sister who was recently unwell with an upper respiratory tract infection that she contracted from kindergarten.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe crawls, plays peek-a-boo, sits independently and has very recently started feeding himself solids at mealtimes. He is growing appropriately and is up to date with immunisations. He was born via normal vaginal delivery at 39 weeks and 6 days gestation after spontaneous onset of labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the baby is awake in his mother\u0027s arms. His vital signs are: pulse rate 116/min, oxygen saturation 95%, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. He has mild chest wall retraction. No episodes of apnoea are noted. Auscultation reveals wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchodilator","Lung function tests","Respiratory viral panel","Chest X-ray","Supportive management"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is bronchiolitis. Bronchiolitis is a clinical diagnosis based on typical history and examination findings, which typically include an acute upper respiratory tract infection with cough, widespread crackles or wheeze, fever, tachypnoea, and subcostal or parasternal retractions. Bronchiolitis is normally a self-resolving condition that generally peaks in severity around day two or three of the illness and resolves after seven to ten days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven that bronchiolitis is normally self-limiting, it is important to stratify the severity (see RCH reference) to prevent the excessive use of diagnostic testing and treatment. With relatively normal behaviour, mild tachypnoea, use of accessory muscles, oxygen saturation \u0026gt;95%, no apnoeic episodes and reduced feeding, this child would be considered to have mild to moderate bronchiolitis. Thus, he may require a brief period of admission with small frequent feeds, regular observations, and parental education.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportantly, most children with bronchiolitis do NOT require any investigations and the \u003Cstrong\u003Emain treatment modality is supportive management\u003C/strong\u003E. Investigations should be considered if diagnostic uncertainty is present (e.g. possible foreign body aspiration) or if the patient deteriorates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled bronchodilators (salbutamol)\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely recommended for the management of bronchiolitis in children. Despite short-term clinical improvement, they do not affect the overall outcome, may have adverse effects, and increase the cost of care. However, these agents may be used in patients with severe bronchiolitis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are unnecessary and are unlikely to be performed successfully in a patient this young.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVirological testing\u003C/strong\u003E does not have a routine role in the management of individual patients as infections are often viral in nature and rarely change the clinical outcome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated and may lead to unnecessary and excessive treatment with antibiotics.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bronchiolitis is a clinical diagnosis and routine investigations are not typically recommended.","Management generally includes supportive therapy in the form of feeds, hydration, antipyretics and oxygen if required."],"references":["The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guidelines: Bronchiolitis [Internet]. The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. 2020. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Bronchiolitis/","Piedra, P., Bronchiolitis in infants and children: Treatment, outcome, and prevention Uptodate.com 2023 [cited 19 Jan 2022]. Available from \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/bronchiolitis-in-infants-and-children-treatment-outcome-and-prevention\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30651"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30651"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-20T17:12:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-20T17:12:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45729"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms"